* * Like you 're 5 * * - because the air 's thinner * * Like you 're 13 * * - as you go higher the air gets thinner . This means that , for every distance , x , you travel , you pass through fewer molecules . If you were travel this distance at the same " true airspeed " at two different altitudes , then at the higher altitude you 'd experience less resistance ( because there are fewer molecules ) , but also the wings would generate less lift ( because there are fewer molecules ) and would behave as if they are going much slower than the really are . This turns out to be so important that pilots rarely use " true airspeed " except for navigation . For everything else , they use " indicated airspeed " , which compensates for the less dense air . If I fly distance x at the same " indicated airspeed " at two different altitudes , then at the higher altitude , I 'd be flying at a higher " true airspeed " , and I 'd cover the distance in less time . The speed at which aircraft cruise is generally a specific indicated airspeed . So at higher altitudes , that would relate to a higher true airspeed . * * Now like you 're an aerodynamics student * * - what I just said is true for light aircraft , but airliners generally travel at close to the speed of sound . However , most planes ca n't break the sound barrier . As you go higher , the air gets thinner , which means the sound of speed decreases . As you go higher , travelling at the same indicated airspeed , your true airspeed goes up , and you also get closer to the speed of sound . Eventually , you have to start decreasing your indicated airspeed to ensurer that your mach number does n't get too high , and you do n't experience shock waves as you approach the sound barrier .
